### TCP Authentication Option (TCP-AO) and PQC
Presented by Tony Lee.
[Slide Deck: tcp-ao](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-tcpm-tcp-ao-00)

*   **Overview:** Discussion on adding Post-Quantum Cryptography (PQC) algorithms to TCP-AO to protect BGP sessions.
*   **Technical Constraint:** Some PQC algorithms require hash lengths that exceed the 40-byte TCP option limit, necessitating "untruncated" versions which require an extended option space.
*   **Discussion:** 
    *   Magnus Westerlund argued that 128-bit truncated tags are likely sufficient for symmetric authentication and that the focus should be on standardizing a reasonable set of modern algorithms.
    *   Alice Mencken supported the move to modern algorithms but encouraged seeking more input from security experts (CFRG) regarding truncation.
    *   Lars Eggert cautioned against "rubber-stamping" requirements from specific customers if they mandate solutions that break standard TCP option limits without a clear technical necessity.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **`draft-ietf-tcpm-ack-rate-request`**: Authors to refine the draft based on API feedback and coordinate with Linux implementers before moving to WGLC.
*   **`draft-boucadair-tcpm-rst-diagnostic-payload`**: The author will remove the freeform description format in the next revision based on security feedback.

## Next Steps
*   The chairs will conduct a poll on the mailing list regarding the adoption of `draft-boucadair-tcpm-rst-diagnostic-payload` after the requested edits are made.
*   The discussion on TCP-AO and PQC requirements, specifically the necessity of untruncated tags and extended option space, will continue on the mailing list.
*   Authors of the TCP Provenance Identifier proposal are encouraged to refine the use case and address privacy/middlebox-transparency concerns.